WEBVTT

00:00:01.440 --> 00:00:08.160
<v Teacher>So we've seen how two sounds in the verbs in the present tense might split when we put pressure on them.

00:00:08.040 --> 00:00:11.640
<v Teacher>We’ve seen how <i>e</i> might become <i>ie</i>,

00:00:11.640 --> 00:00:17.320
<v Teacher>so for example we have <b>querer</b> which means <i>to </i> <i>want</i>, but <i>I want </i>is:

00:00:18.020 --> 00:00:18.820
<v Student><b>Quiero.</b>

00:00:19.460 --> 00:00:23.060
<v Teacher>So we stress down on that e and it splits into ie.

00:00:23.060 --> 00:00:25.780
<v Teacher>And this will happen for the other versions that we learned as well.

00:00:25.780 --> 00:00:29.620
<v Teacher>So how do you say <i>he wants </i>or <i>she wants </i>or <i>you</i> (formal) <i>want</i>?

00:00:29.680 --> 00:00:30.560
<v Student><b>Quiere.</b>

00:00:30.560 --> 00:00:31.680
<v Teacher>Quiere.

00:00:31.680 --> 00:00:33.760
<v Teacher>They want:

00:00:33.760 --> 00:00:34.560
<v Student><b>Quieren.</b>

00:00:34.560 --> 00:00:35.120
<v Teacher>Quieren.

00:00:35.120 --> 00:00:35.360
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:35.360 --> 00:00:37.360
<v Teacher>And <i>you</i> (informal):

00:00:37.360 --> 00:00:38.160
<v Student><b>Quieres.</b>

00:00:38.160 --> 00:00:38.400
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:38.400 --> 00:00:39.760
<v Teacher><i>What do you want?</i>:

00:00:40.720 --> 00:00:41.600
<v Student><b>¿Qué quieres?</b>

00:00:41.760 --> 00:00:43.120
<v Teacher>Yeah. ¿Qué quieres?

00:00:43.120 --> 00:00:43.680
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:43.680 --> 00:00:49.440
<v Teacher>So another example where this will happen is with the verb <b>perder</b>, which means <i>to lose</i>.

00:00:49.440 --> 00:00:51.920
<v Teacher>It's related to <i>perish</i>.

00:00:51.920 --> 00:00:54.239
<v Teacher>So how would you say: <i>I lose</i>?

00:00:54.480 --> 00:00:55.360
<v Student><b>Pierdo.</b>

00:00:55.360 --> 00:00:56.000
<v Teacher>Pierdo.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:56.320
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:56.320 --> 00:00:59.600
<v Teacher>And <i>he loses</i>, <i>she loses</i>:

00:00:59.600 --> 00:01:00.239
<v Student><b>Pierde.</b>

00:01:00.239 --> 00:01:00.960
<v Teacher><b>Pierde.</b>

00:01:00.960 --> 00:01:02.320
<v Teacher><i>They</i>:

00:01:02.320 --> 00:01:03.200
<v Student><b>Pierden.</b>

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:03.600
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:03.600 --> 00:01:05.520
<v Teacher>And <i>you</i> (informal):

00:01:05.880 --> 00:01:06.840
<v Student><b>Pierdes.</b>

00:01:06.840 --> 00:01:07.720
<v Teacher><b>Pierdes.</b>

00:01:07.720 --> 00:01:08.520
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:08.520 --> 00:01:13.720
<v Teacher>So we saw that the <i>e</i> can split into <i>ie</i>, and

00:01:14.240 --> 00:01:20.640
<v Teacher>we also saw that an <i>o </i>in the base of the verb can split into <i>ue.</i>

00:01:20.640 --> 00:01:24.720
<v Teacher>So we saw, for example, <b>poder</b> is <i>to be able</i>.

00:01:24.800 --> 00:01:28.640
<v Teacher>And then we have <b>puedo</b>, <i>I </i> <i>can, I am able</i>.

00:01:28.960 --> 00:01:30.800
<v Teacher>We had <b>dormir</b>,

00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:32.880
<v Teacher>what did <b>dormir</b> mean?

00:01:33.200 --> 00:01:34.080
<v Student><i>To sleep.</i>

00:01:34.080 --> 00:01:34.400
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:34.400 --> 00:01:35.760
<v Teacher>And <b>duermo</b>:

00:01:36.980 --> 00:01:37.940
<v Student><i>I sleep.</i>

00:01:37.940 --> 00:01:38.580
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:38.580 --> 00:01:42.180
<v Teacher>What changed when we added <b>me</b>? <b>Me duermo</b>:

00:01:42.180 --> 00:01:44.500
<v Student>I think it's <i>I fall asleep</i>.

00:01:44.500 --> 00:01:44.979
<v Teacher>Yes.

00:01:44.979 --> 00:01:47.300
<v Teacher><i>I sleep myself</i>, <i>I fall asleep</i>.

00:01:47.300 --> 00:01:47.860
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:47.920 --> 00:01:52.320
<v Teacher>So we can expect to see these <i>o</i>'s split, but not always.

00:01:52.320 --> 00:01:58.400
<v Teacher>For example, <i>to eat</i> was? <i>To eat</i>: <b>Comer.</b> <b>Comer. </b>And <i>I eat</i>:

00:01:59.280 --> 00:02:01.520
<v Teacher><b>Como. </b>So it didn't split there.

00:02:01.520 --> 00:02:04.400
<v Teacher>So there's no way to know where it will, where it won't.

00:02:04.400 --> 00:02:12.640
<v Teacher>Most of the time it will and you just have to kind of experiment and see what happens. And you will always get the feedback when you try to see if it splits or not.

00:02:12.240 --> 00:02:15.840
<v Teacher>You'll also develop an intuition of where you should do it.

00:02:15.840 --> 00:02:20.400
<v Teacher>So <b>colgar</b>, for example, is <i>to hang</i>.

00:02:20.400 --> 00:02:23.200
<v Teacher>So if you want to say <i>I hang</i>:

00:02:23.480 --> 00:02:24.440
<v Student><b>Cuelgo.</b>

00:02:24.440 --> 00:02:25.240
<v Teacher>Cuelgo.

00:02:25.240 --> 00:02:25.960
<v Teacher>Good.

00:02:25.960 --> 00:02:28.040
<v Teacher><i>He hangs</i>:

00:02:28.040 --> 00:02:31.640
<v Student><b>Cuelge</b>, no it's <b>colgar</b>, so it's <b>cuelga</b>.

00:02:31.640 --> 00:02:35.700
<v Teacher><b>Cuelga.</b> Why do you think you said <b>cuelge</b> first?

00:02:35.700 --> 00:02:44.820
<v Student>Well the reason you explained before with the- because it has an /<i>e</i>/ sound before, it seems to go more.

00:02:44.960 --> 00:02:48.000
<v Teacher>Exactly, it fits more. So you will find yourself doing that.

00:02:48.560 --> 00:02:54.560
<v Teacher>How do you get out of doing that, how do you stop that happening?

00:02:54.640 --> 00:02:58.880
<v Student>By going back to the “to” version of the verb.

00:02:58.880 --> 00:02:59.840
<v Teacher>Exactly,

00:02:59.840 --> 00:03:01.520
<v Teacher>and then you're in control.

00:03:01.520 --> 00:03:04.160
<v Teacher><b>Colgar</b>, -<i>ar</i> verb, <b>cuelga</b>.

00:03:04.160 --> 00:03:04.800
<v Teacher>Good.

00:03:04.800 --> 00:03:05.520
<v Teacher><i>They hang</i>:

00:03:06.580 --> 00:03:07.540
<v Student><b>Cuelgan.</b>

00:03:07.540 --> 00:03:07.860
<v Teacher>Good.

00:03:07.860 --> 00:03:09.700
<v Teacher><i>They hang it</i>:

00:03:09.700 --> 00:03:10.820
<v Student><b>Lo cuelgan.</b>

00:03:10.820 --> 00:03:12.020
<v Teacher>Lo cuelgan.

00:03:12.020 --> 00:03:14.420
<v Teacher>They hang them:

00:03:14.420 --> 00:03:15.780
<v Student><b>Los cuelgan.</b>

00:03:15.780 --> 00:03:16.180
<v Teacher>Good.

00:03:16.180 --> 00:03:18.100
<v Teacher><i>She hangs them</i>:

00:03:18.440 --> 00:03:19.720
<v Student><b>Los cuelga.</b>

00:03:19.720 --> 00:03:21.640
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Los cuelga.</b>

00:03:21.640 --> 00:03:32.440
<v Teacher>Words in English that begin <i>al-</i>, so not end -<i>al</i> like <i>normal</i>, <b>normal</b>, <i>metal</i>, <b>metal</b>, they begin <i>al</i>-, they come from Arabic.

00:03:32.379 --> 00:03:38.700
<v Teacher>This <i>al-</i> means <i>the</i> in Arabic. And in Arabic it's written with the word.

00:03:38.700 --> 00:03:39.819
<v Teacher>It's written as one word.

00:03:39.819 --> 00:03:40.860
<v Teacher>It's all stuck together.

00:03:40.860 --> 00:03:44.299
<v Teacher>So when words came in from Arabic they kind of came in most of the time

00:03:43.960 --> 00:03:54.200
<v Teacher><i>the</i>. So for example, <i>alcohol</i>, and when we say <i>the alcohol</i>, we are actually saying something like "the the alcohol", something like this.

00:03:54.340 --> 00:03:57.300
<v Teacher>The verb <i>to take</i> is <b>tomar</b>.

00:03:57.300 --> 00:03:58.020
<v Teacher><b>Tomar.</b>

00:03:58.020 --> 00:03:59.700
<v Teacher><i>T-o-m-a-r</i>.

00:03:59.700 --> 00:04:00.420
<v Student><b>Tomar.</b>

00:04:00.420 --> 00:04:00.980
<v Teacher>Tomar.

00:04:00.980 --> 00:04:03.140
<v Teacher>And this is also used like to drink.

00:04:03.140 --> 00:04:06.020
<v Teacher>So it's used like <i>take</i>

00:04:05.820 --> 00:04:15.180
<v Teacher>generically, generally, but also <i>to </i> <i>drink</i>. How would you say: <i>I don't drink alcohol, I don't take alcohol</i>?

00:04:16.299 --> 00:04:18.620
<v Student><b>No tomo alcohol.</b>

00:04:18.620 --> 00:04:19.019
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:19.019 --> 00:04:21.100
<v Teacher>No tomo alcohol.

00:04:21.100 --> 00:04:24.700
<v Teacher>Sugar in Spanish is azucar.

00:04:24.700 --> 00:04:25.820
<v Student><b>Azucar.</b>

00:04:25.820 --> 00:04:26.860
<v Teacher>Azucar.

00:04:26.860 --> 00:04:27.980
<v Teacher><b>Azucar.</b>

00:04:27.980 --> 00:04:32.140
<v Teacher>Or in Spain because we have a z here, it will be /athucar/ in most of Spain.

00:04:32.140 --> 00:04:37.100
<v Teacher>Now, this is also an Arabic word, and it's the same word as <i>sugar</i> in English.

00:04:37.100 --> 00:04:38.540
<v Teacher>Might not look like it.

00:04:38.620 --> 00:04:40.060
<v Teacher>What's happened here?

00:04:40.060 --> 00:04:50.379
<v Teacher>In Arabic, the <i>l</i> of <i>al</i> - the word for <i>the</i> - assimilates, changes to match the next letter if the next letter is kind of close to it.

00:04:50.379 --> 00:04:52.539
<v Teacher>It does this with about half the letters.

00:04:52.100 --> 00:04:56.900
<v Teacher>So in Arabic actually, instead of <b>alzucar</b>, you say <b>azucar</b>.

00:04:56.900 --> 00:04:58.820
<v Teacher>And this passed into Spanish.

00:04:58.820 --> 00:05:02.260
<v Teacher>But in English we got the word without the <i>the</i> at the beginning this time.

00:05:02.260 --> 00:05:05.220
<v Teacher>This time <i>sugar</i> came in without the <i>the</i> at the beginning.

00:05:05.220 --> 00:05:06.900
<v Teacher>So they look kind of different,

00:05:06.580 --> 00:05:18.180
<v Teacher>and sound rather different: sugar, azucar. But again they're the same word. So how would you say: I don't take sugar? No tomo azucar. Good. No tomo azucar.

00:05:18.880 --> 00:05:22.800
<v Teacher>Arroz, rice, is also an Arabic word.

00:05:22.800 --> 00:05:26.160
<v Teacher>It's actually <b>al ruz</b>, <i>the rice</i>.

00:05:26.160 --> 00:05:33.280
<v Teacher>But again in Spanish, the <i>l</i> assimilated to the next <i>r</i>, as it does in Arabic

00:05:33.420 --> 00:05:39.340
<v Teacher>and instead of <b>al ruz </b>like in arabic, <b>arruz</b>, we ended up with <b>arroz</b>.

00:05:39.340 --> 00:05:40.620
<v Student>So it's two <i>r</i>'s?

00:05:40.620 --> 00:05:41.740
<v Teacher>Two <i>r</i>'s.

00:05:41.200 --> 00:05:44.160
<v Student>So is <b>azucar</b> with two <i>s</i>'s?

00:05:44.160 --> 00:05:46.480
<v Teacher>Nope. It's with a <i>z</i> here

00:05:46.480 --> 00:05:50.480
<v Teacher>because two <i>s</i>'s are not a combination you find in Spanish.

00:05:50.480 --> 00:05:52.880
<v Teacher>So for example, in the word <i>possible</i>,

00:05:52.900 --> 00:05:54.500
<v Teacher>we have two <i>s</i>'s there in English.

00:05:54.500 --> 00:05:58.020
<v Teacher>But in Spanish when we write <b>posible</b>, we write one <i>s</i>.

00:05:58.020 --> 00:05:59.620
<v Teacher>The same with <i>passion</i>;

00:05:59.620 --> 00:06:00.900
<v Teacher>we write one <i>s</i>

00:06:01.039 --> 00:06:02.879
<v Teacher>in Spanish, <b>pasión</b>.

00:06:02.879 --> 00:06:10.560
<v Teacher>So you don't get two <i>s</i>'s together in Spanish. But you do get two <i>r</i>'s together to differentiate between the normal <i>r</i> and the rolling <i>r</i>.

00:06:10.060 --> 00:06:12.940
<v Teacher>So in Spanish we have <i>a-r-r-o-z</i>.

00:06:13.020 --> 00:06:18.300
<v Teacher>It's just assimilation of <b>al ruz: arruz</b>, to Spanish <b>arroz</b>.

00:06:18.300 --> 00:06:20.860
<v Teacher>And it's the same word that's in English, <i>rice.</i>

00:06:20.860 --> 00:06:23.020
<v Teacher>So how do you say: <i>I want rice</i>?

00:06:23.740 --> 00:06:25.020
<v Student><b>Quiero arroz.</b>

00:06:25.020 --> 00:06:26.140
<v Teacher>Quiero arroz.

00:06:26.140 --> 00:06:26.940
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:26.940 --> 00:06:27.980
<v Teacher><i>Algebra</i>.

00:06:27.980 --> 00:06:30.140
<v Teacher>How would that be in Spanish?

00:06:30.780 --> 00:06:31.980
<v Student><b>Algebra.</b>

00:06:32.220 --> 00:06:33.340
<v Teacher>/<i>Al-heh-bra</i>/

00:06:33.340 --> 00:06:34.860
<v Student><b>Algebra.</b>

00:06:34.860 --> 00:06:36.700
<v Teacher><b>Algebra.</b> Good.

00:06:36.600 --> 00:06:46.360
<v Teacher>Spanish has a lot more Arabic than English. The south of Spain was part of the Muslim world for 800 years, so the languages had a lot of contact.

00:06:45.760 --> 00:06:49.840
<v Teacher>And you get more words in Spanish that you don't have in English that are from Arabic.

00:06:49.840 --> 00:06:53.200
<v Teacher>So for example, <b>aceite</b>, <i>oil</i>.

00:06:53.200 --> 00:06:55.280
<v Teacher>In Arabic this is <b>zet</b>.

00:06:55.280 --> 00:06:56.400
<v Teacher><b>Aceite</b>.

00:06:56.900 --> 00:07:08.820
<v Teacher><b>Aceituna</b>, <i>olive</i>, <b>zetun</b> in Arabic. <b>Alfombra</b>, which means <i>carpet</i>, <b>almohada</b>, which means <i>pillow</i>, all of these words they came in from Arabic.

00:07:08.820 --> 00:07:10.660
<v Teacher>When you find <i>al-</i> at the beginning,

00:07:10.760 --> 00:07:14.120
<v Teacher>with maybe a couple of exceptions, it's from Arabic.

00:07:14.120 --> 00:07:16.920
<v Teacher>So we said <i>I take </i>is <b>tomo</b>.

00:07:16.920 --> 00:07:21.240
<v Teacher>How is: <i>he takes, she takes, it takes, you </i>(formal) <i>take</i>?

00:07:22.140 --> 00:07:22.940
<v Student><b>Toma.</b>

00:07:22.940 --> 00:07:24.140
<v Teacher><b>Toma.</b> Good.

00:07:24.140 --> 00:07:27.020
<v Teacher><i>You</i> (informal)? Talking to a friend:

00:07:27.340 --> 00:07:28.140
<v Student><b>Tomas.</b>

00:07:28.140 --> 00:07:28.380
<v Teacher>Good.

00:07:28.380 --> 00:07:33.500
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>what are you taking?</i> This could be a way to ask <i>what do you want to drink?</i>

00:07:34.800 --> 00:07:35.680
<v Student>¿<b>Qué tomas?</b>

00:07:35.680 --> 00:07:36.880
<v Teacher>¿<b>Qué tomas?</b> <i>To drink</i> exists.

00:07:36.880 --> 00:07:42.800
<v Teacher>It's <b>beber</b>,<b> beber</b>. And the word <i>drink</i>, the noun: <b>una bebida</b>,

00:07:42.580 --> 00:07:43.860
<v Teacher><i>a </i> <i>drink</i>.

00:07:43.860 --> 00:07:46.180
<v Teacher><b>Una,</b> we have <i>a </i>for feminine words

00:07:46.180 --> 00:07:49.780
<v Teacher><b>una bebida </b>or <b>la bebida</b>, <i>the drink</i>, comes from <b>beber</b>.

00:07:49.780 --> 00:07:53.140
<v Teacher>But <b>tomar</b>, <i>to take</i>, is extremely common.

00:07:53.900 --> 00:07:57.260
<v Teacher><i>They take</i>: <b>Toman.</b>

00:07:57.260 --> 00:07:58.300
<v Teacher>Toman.

00:07:58.300 --> 00:07:59.100
<v Teacher>Good.

00:07:59.100 --> 00:08:05.980
<v Teacher>Now there's one more version of the verbs that we didn't learn yet, which was the “we” version.

00:08:05.840 --> 00:08:09.200
<v Teacher>We didn't learn how to say <i>we want</i> or <i>we have</i>.

00:08:09.200 --> 00:08:12.560
<v Teacher>Now <i>we take </i>is <b>tomamos</b>.

00:08:12.560 --> 00:08:13.440
<v Teacher><b>Tomamos.</b>

00:08:13.440 --> 00:08:16.240
<v Teacher>Explain to me what I did then to get <i>we take</i>.

00:08:16.240 --> 00:08:20.000
<v Teacher>If I go from <b>tomar</b> to <b>tomamos</b> what am I doing?

00:08:20.759 --> 00:08:24.360
<v Student>You took out the -<i>r</i> and put a -<i>mos</i> at the end.

00:08:24.360 --> 00:08:28.120
<v Teacher>But to make it fit in with your- Well you took out the -<i>ar</i>,

00:08:28.639 --> 00:08:32.640
<v Student>the -<i>ar</i> sound, and you put in the -<i>amos</i> sound.

00:08:32.640 --> 00:08:38.719
<v Teacher>This is very nice to think about it this way because then you fit it in with what you've been doing up until now.

00:08:38.360 --> 00:08:41.080
<v Teacher>Taking off the -<i>ar</i>, <i>a-r</i>, and putting in your ending.

00:08:41.080 --> 00:08:45.400
<v Teacher>So you take off -<i>ar</i> and you put on -<i>amos</i> and you get the “we” form.

00:08:45.400 --> 00:08:47.880
<v Teacher>So, how is: <i>to speak</i>?

00:08:47.880 --> 00:08:48.680
<v Student><b>Hablar.</b>

00:08:49.480 --> 00:08:50.680
<v Teacher>And we speak:

00:08:51.560 --> 00:08:52.440
<v Student><b>Hablamos.</b>

00:08:52.440 --> 00:08:53.240
<v Teacher>Hablamos.

00:08:53.240 --> 00:08:54.120
<v Teacher>Good.

00:08:54.120 --> 00:08:58.600
<v Teacher>So with -<i>amos</i> we're adding on two syllables, and the accent

00:08:58.959 --> 00:09:00.800
<v Teacher>is going on the second last syllable.

00:09:00.800 --> 00:09:05.360
<v Teacher>So it's in a different position, that accent, to the other versions.

00:09:05.360 --> 00:09:11.440
<v Teacher>If we look at <b>tomo, toma, toman, tomas, tomamos</b>,

00:09:11.339 --> 00:09:12.860
<v Teacher>the accent is moving.

00:09:12.860 --> 00:09:15.019
<v Teacher>Again, <i>to speak</i>:

00:09:15.019 --> 00:09:15.980
<v Student><b>Hablar.</b>

00:09:15.980 --> 00:09:17.500
<v Teacher><i>I speak</i>:

00:09:17.500 --> 00:09:18.459
<v Student><b>Hablo.</b>

00:09:18.459 --> 00:09:20.139
<v Teacher><i>She speaks</i>:

00:09:20.800 --> 00:09:21.600
<v Student><b>Habla.</b>

00:09:21.600 --> 00:09:22.320
<v Teacher>Habla.

00:09:22.320 --> 00:09:23.600
<v Teacher>They speak:

00:09:23.600 --> 00:09:24.640
<v Student><b>Hablan.</b>

00:09:24.640 --> 00:09:26.880
<v Teacher><i>You</i> (informal):

00:09:27.200 --> 00:09:28.160
<v Student><b>Hablas.</b>

00:09:28.160 --> 00:09:28.480
<v Teacher><i>We</i>:

00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:30.160
<v Student><b>Hablamos.</b>

00:09:31.279 --> 00:09:32.240
<v Teacher>Good.

00:09:32.240 --> 00:09:37.120
<v Teacher>So this affects the split of the <i>e</i>

00:09:37.620 --> 00:09:43.380
<v Teacher>or the <i>o</i> in the root of the verb. Because we said that it splits because you stress it.

00:09:43.380 --> 00:09:46.100
<v Teacher>But in the “we” form we don't actually stress it.

00:09:46.100 --> 00:09:47.459
<v Teacher>So let's look at this.

00:09:47.459 --> 00:09:52.260
<v Teacher>What was <i>to find</i> or <i>to encounter</i>?

00:09:54.700 --> 00:09:55.700
<v Student><b>Encontrar.</b>

00:09:55.700 --> 00:09:56.700
<v Teacher><b>Encontrar.</b> <i>I find</i>:

00:09:56.700 --> 00:09:58.180
<v Student><b>Encuentro.</b>

00:09:58.180 --> 00:10:01.180
<v Teacher><b>Encuentro.</b> <i>I find</i> or <i>I'm finding</i>.

00:10:01.180 --> 00:10:02.140
<v Teacher><i>He finds</i>:

00:10:03.560 --> 00:10:05.000
<v Student><b>Encuentra.</b>

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:05.959
<v Teacher><b>Encuentra.</b>

00:10:05.959 --> 00:10:06.440
<v Teacher>Good.

00:10:06.440 --> 00:10:08.680
<v Teacher>You went back to the "to" form, right?

00:10:08.680 --> 00:10:09.639
<v Student>Yep.

00:10:09.959 --> 00:10:10.519
<v Teacher><i>They</i>:

00:10:12.260 --> 00:10:13.459
<v Student><b>Encuentran.</b>

00:10:13.459 --> 00:10:13.940
<v Teacher>Good.

00:10:13.940 --> 00:10:17.220
<v Teacher>And <i>you</i> (informal):

00:10:17.220 --> 00:10:18.339
<v Student><b>Encuentras.</b>

00:10:18.339 --> 00:10:18.740
<v Teacher>Good.

00:10:18.740 --> 00:10:22.339
<v Teacher>Now <i>we</i>. You're not stressing that <i>o</i> anymore so it's safe.

00:10:22.339 --> 00:10:24.260
<v Teacher>It's not going to split.

00:10:25.060 --> 00:10:26.259
<v Student><b>Encontramos.</b>

00:10:26.259 --> 00:10:26.980
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:10:26.980 --> 00:10:28.019
<v Teacher>Encontramos.

00:10:28.019 --> 00:10:30.259
<v Teacher>We don't stress it, so it doesn't split.

00:10:30.259 --> 00:10:33.380
<v Teacher>What was <i>demonstration</i>?

00:10:33.860 --> 00:10:40.740
<v Student><b>Demonstración. Demostración.</b>

00:10:40.740 --> 00:10:41.600
<v Teacher><b>Demostración.</b> So how would you say: <i>to demonstrate</i>?

00:10:41.600 --> 00:10:42.480
<v Student><b>Demostrar.</b>

00:10:42.640 --> 00:10:43.680
<v Teacher><b>Demostrar.</b>

00:10:43.680 --> 00:10:49.680
<v Teacher>If you take away this de-, which actually means of in Spanish. If you get rid of it you're left with mostrar

00:10:49.680 --> 00:10:51.120
<v Teacher>and what does <b>mostrar</b> mean?

00:10:51.120 --> 00:10:51.840
<v Student><i>To show.</i>

00:10:51.840 --> 00:10:52.800
<v Teacher>To show.

00:10:52.800 --> 00:10:55.760
<v Teacher>I show or I'm showing:

00:10:56.320 --> 00:10:57.200
<v Student><b>Mostro.</b>

00:10:57.200 --> 00:10:59.680
<v Teacher>It should be <b>mostro</b>, but-

00:10:59.680 --> 00:11:00.640
<v Student><b>Muestro.</b>

00:11:00.640 --> 00:11:01.440
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Muestro.</b>

00:11:01.440 --> 00:11:03.760
<v Teacher>And <i>he</i>, or <i>she/it/you</i> (formal):

00:11:04.140 --> 00:11:05.100
<v Student><b>Muestra.</b>

00:11:05.100 --> 00:11:05.580
<v Teacher>Good.

00:11:05.580 --> 00:11:07.980
<v Teacher><i>They</i> or <i>you guys</i>:

00:11:07.980 --> 00:11:09.020
<v Student><b>Muestran.</b>

00:11:09.020 --> 00:11:09.740
<v Teacher>Muestran.

00:11:09.740 --> 00:11:11.900
<v Teacher>You (informal):

00:11:11.900 --> 00:11:13.100
<v Student><b>Muestras.</b>

00:11:13.100 --> 00:11:13.340
<v Teacher><i>We</i>:

00:11:14.560 --> 00:11:15.600
<v Student><b>Mostramos.</b>

00:11:15.600 --> 00:11:16.160
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:11:16.160 --> 00:11:17.040
<v Teacher>Mostramos.

00:11:17.040 --> 00:11:20.320
<v Teacher>You're not accenting anymore that o, so it doesn't split.

00:11:20.320 --> 00:11:21.520
<v Teacher>Mostramos.

00:11:21.520 --> 00:11:23.440
<v Teacher>How do you say <i>to think</i>?

00:11:23.440 --> 00:11:26.800
<v Teacher>And we said it's related to the word <i>pensive</i>.

00:11:26.740 --> 00:11:27.699
<v Student><b>Pensar.</b>

00:11:27.699 --> 00:11:28.579
<v Teacher>Pensar.

00:11:28.579 --> 00:11:29.220
<v Teacher>Good.

00:11:29.220 --> 00:11:31.060
<v Teacher><i>I think</i>:

00:11:31.060 --> 00:11:31.860
<v Student><b>Pienso.</b>

00:11:31.860 --> 00:11:32.500
<v Teacher>Pienso.

00:11:32.500 --> 00:11:34.899
<v Teacher>There the e splits when we stress it.

00:11:34.459 --> 00:11:38.459
<v Teacher>If you want to say <i>I think so</i>, you can just say <i>I think </i> <i>that yes</i>.

00:11:38.459 --> 00:11:39.980
<v Teacher><i>I think that yes</i>.

00:11:39.980 --> 00:11:42.300
<v Teacher><i>That</i> is the same as what?

00:11:42.459 --> 00:11:43.260
<v Student>Que.

00:11:43.260 --> 00:11:44.459
<v Student>Pienso que sí.

00:11:44.459 --> 00:11:45.580
<v Teacher>Pienso que sí. I

00:11:45.580 --> 00:11:46.140
<v Teacher>think so,

00:11:46.140 --> 00:11:47.500
<v Teacher><b>pienso que sí</b>.

00:11:47.500 --> 00:11:47.980
<v Teacher>Good.

00:11:48.320 --> 00:11:53.040
<v Teacher><i>He thinks </i>or <i>she thinks</i>, <i>you </i>(formal) <i>think</i>:

00:11:53.040 --> 00:11:53.920
<v Student><b>Piensa.</b>

00:11:53.920 --> 00:11:54.320
<v Teacher>Good.

00:11:54.320 --> 00:11:55.120
<v Teacher>Piensa.

00:11:55.120 --> 00:11:56.640
<v Teacher>They:

00:11:56.640 --> 00:11:57.760
<v Student><b>Piensan.</b>

00:11:57.760 --> 00:11:59.760
<v Teacher><i>You</i> (informal):

00:11:59.760 --> 00:12:00.720
<v Student><b>Piensas.</b>

00:12:00.720 --> 00:12:02.400
<v Teacher><i>What do you think?:</i>

00:12:04.180 --> 00:12:04.500
<v Teacher>Good.

00:12:04.500 --> 00:12:09.540
<v Teacher>If you say <i>what do you think to do</i>, we said that this means <i>what do you plan on doing</i>.

00:12:09.540 --> 00:12:11.540
<v Teacher>You can just say <i>what do you think to do</i>.

00:12:11.540 --> 00:12:12.579
<v Teacher>What was <i>to do</i>?

00:12:12.579 --> 00:12:13.620
<v Teacher>To do or to make

00:12:13.620 --> 00:12:15.139
<v Teacher>which begins with a silent h:

00:12:16.440 --> 00:12:17.320
<v Student><b>Hacer.</b>

00:12:17.320 --> 00:12:18.519
<v Teacher><b>Hacer.</b> Good.

00:12:18.519 --> 00:12:20.120
<v Teacher>So what do you think to do,

00:12:20.120 --> 00:12:22.040
<v Teacher>what do you plan on doing?:

00:12:23.320 --> 00:12:24.360
<v Student><b>Qué</b>-

00:12:24.160 --> 00:12:25.280
<v Student>You informal? <b>Qué piensas hacer.</b>

00:12:27.840 --> 00:12:28.320
<v Teacher>Good.

00:12:28.320 --> 00:12:30.000
<v Teacher>Qué piensas hacer.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:32.480
<v Teacher>Now how would you say: we think?

00:12:33.500 --> 00:12:34.620
<v Student><b>Pensamos.</b>

00:12:34.620 --> 00:12:35.100
<v Teacher>Good.

00:12:35.100 --> 00:12:36.060
<v Teacher><b>Pensamos.</b>

00:12:36.060 --> 00:12:37.740
<v Teacher>So you're not splitting there.

00:12:37.740 --> 00:12:39.340
<v Teacher><b>Pensamos.</b>

00:12:39.340 --> 00:12:43.660
<v Teacher>The verb <i>to close</i>, <i>to close</i>, is <b>cerrar</b>.

00:12:43.660 --> 00:12:47.580
<v Teacher><i>c-e-r-r-a-r</i>. <b>Cerrar.</b>

00:12:47.380 --> 00:12:48.260
<v Student><b>Cerrar.</b>

00:12:48.260 --> 00:12:48.740
<v Teacher>Good.

00:12:48.740 --> 00:12:51.460
<v Teacher>Or in most of Spain, /<i>therrar</i>/.

00:12:51.460 --> 00:12:54.020
<v Teacher>How would you say: <i>I close</i>?

00:12:54.340 --> 00:12:55.300
<v Student><b>Cierro.</b>

00:12:55.300 --> 00:12:56.100
<v Teacher><b>Cierro.</b>

00:12:56.100 --> 00:12:56.740
<v Teacher>Good.

00:12:56.740 --> 00:13:01.700
<v Teacher><i>She closes, he closes, you</i> (formal) <i>close</i>:

00:13:01.240 --> 00:13:02.120
<v Student><b>Cierra.</b>

00:13:02.120 --> 00:13:02.920
<v Teacher><b>Cierra.</b>

00:13:02.920 --> 00:13:03.480
<v Teacher>Good.

00:13:03.480 --> 00:13:07.720
<v Teacher>So how would you say: <i>we close</i>?

00:13:07.720 --> 00:13:08.759
<v Student><b>Cerramos.</b>

00:13:08.759 --> 00:13:09.639
<v Teacher>Good.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:18.680
<v Teacher>So we're seeing that really this issue of the <i>e</i>'s and the <i>o</i>'s splitting is an issue about stress, and it’s only when we stress them down that they split under that pressure.

00:13:18.840 --> 00:13:22.920
<v Teacher>When we don't, they are intact.